  <section>
    <h2>CSS Reference</h2>
    <code-block language="css" show-lines label="mark CSS">{{ markCssCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <p>The default highlight uses relative oklch color derived from the theme's interactive color, so it adapts automatically to each theme. The status variants use fixed oklch values at 20% opacity for consistent, transparent overlays.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Highlight Effect</h2>
    <p>VB's <a href="/docs/attributes/data-effect/#highlight"><code>data-effect="highlight"</code></a> provides an animated version of mark-style highlighting that draws in on scroll. This is a CSS animation, not the <code>&lt;mark&gt;</code> element &mdash; but they share the same visual language.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Accessibility</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Some screen readers announce marked text, though support varies</li>
      <li>Don't rely solely on highlight color to convey meaning &mdash; add text labels for status variants</li>
      <li>Ensure sufficient contrast between highlighted text and background</li>
      <li>Provide context for why text is highlighted (e.g., "Search results for...")</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Adding Screen Reader Context</h3>
    <p>For status variants, add a <code>visually-hidden</code> label so screen readers announce the state:</p>

    <browser-window src="/docs/snippets/demos/mark-accessible.html" url="mark-accessible.html" title="Accessible mark" shadow></browser-window>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Accessible mark with hidden context">{{ accessibleMarkCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

